hooks claude-code stop\",\"durationMs\":292}],\"hookErrors\":[],\"preventedContinuation\":false,\"stopReason\":\"\",\"hasOutput\":true,\"level\":\"suggestion\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-02-25T01:21:58.461Z\",\"uuid\":\"ad5d9da5-952c-4c9d-b9e7-723f37e6fea5\",\"toolUseID\":\"6d6a1f41-d946-4140-baa4-33d6be7b5e71\"}\n{\"type\":\"queue-operation\",\"operation\":\"enqueue\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-02-25T01:22:33.061Z\",\"sessionId\":\"7b61ce6f-2b9a-4e37-8527-229cc2bcbfe9\",\"content\":\"<task-notification>\\n<task-id>af4878787b32c67fe</task-id>\\n<tool-use-id>toolu_01N7H9qD5JdWfpWivkDvHv6i</tool-use-id>\\n<status>completed</status>\\n<summary>Agent \\\"Review strategy layer changes\\\" completed</summary>\\n<result>Good. Now I have confirmed all the key findings. Here is the complete review.\\n\\n---\\n\\n# Code Review: `improve-context-management` Branch -- Strategy Layer\\n\\n## Scope\\n\\nBranch `improve-context-management` vs HEAD, filtered to:\\n- `/Users/pfleidi/entire/cli/cmd/entire/cli/strategy/` (all files)\\n- `/Users/pfleidi/entire/cli/cmd/entire/cli/checkpoint/` (committed.go, temporary.go)\\n- `/Users/pfleidi/entire/cli/cmd/entire/cli/session/` (phase.go, state.go)\\n\\n42 files changed, ~1144 insertions, ~1127 deletions.\\n\\n## Overview\\n\\nThis change threads `context.Context` through approximately 80+ function signatures across the strategy, checkpoint, and session packages. It replaces ad-hoc `context.Background()` calls with properly propagated contexts, enabling cancellation, deadlines, and tracing throughout the call stack. The refactoring also renames `ctx StepContext` parameters to `step StepContext` where the name would shadow the new `context.Context` parameter.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Critical (Must Fix)\\n\\n### C1. sync.Once captures first caller's context for git subprocess execution\\n\\n**`/Users/pfleidi/entire/cli/cmd/entire/cli/strategy/manual_commit.go:33-42`**\\n\\n`getStateStore(ctx)` passes the caller's `context.Context` into `sync.Once`. Inside the closure, `NewStateStore(ctx)` calls `getGitCommonDir(ctx)` which runs `exec.CommandContext(ctx, \\\"git\\\", \\\"rev-parse\\\", \\\"--git-common-dir\\\")`. If the first caller's context is already cancelled or is cancelled during the subprocess execution, the git command fails and the error is cached permanently by `sync.Once`. All subsequent callers will receive the cached error, even though they pass valid contexts.\\n\\n```go\\n// manual_commit.go:33-42\\nfunc (s *ManualCommitStrategy) getStateStore(ctx context.Context) (*session.StateStore, error) {\\n    s.stateStoreOnce.Do(func() {\\n        store, err := session.NewStateStore(ctx)  // ctx from first caller only\\n        if err != nil {\\n            s.stateStoreErr = fmt.Errorf(\\\"failed to create state store: %w\\\", err)\\n            return\\n        }\\n        s.stateStore = store\\n    })\\n    return s.stateStore, s.stateStoreErr\\n}\\n```\\n\\nCompare with `getCheckpointStore()` on line 47-57, which correctly uses `context.Background()` inside its `sync.Once`:\\n\\n```go\\n// manual_commit.go:47-57\\nfunc (s *ManualCommitStrategy) getCheckpointStore() (*checkpoint.GitStore, error) {\\n    s.checkpointStoreOnce.Do(func() {\\n        repo, err := OpenRepository(context.Background())  // Correct: background context\\n        // ...\\n    })\\n    return s.checkpointStore, s.checkpointStoreErr\\n}\\n```\\n\\n**Suggested fix:** Use `context.Background()` inside the `sync.Once` closure, consistent with `getCheckpointStore()`:\\n\\n```go\\ns.stateStoreOnce.Do(func() {\\n    store, err := session.NewStateStore(context.Background())\\n    // ...\\n})\\n```\\n\\nThe context is only used for a one-time directory lookup (`git rev-parse --git-common-dir`). Using `context.Background()` here is safe and correct -- the initialization is a one-time setup operation that should not be tied to any particular request's lifecycle.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Important (Should Fix)\\n\\n### I1. EnsureSetup is the only Strategy interface method without context.Context\\n\\n**`/Users/pfleidi/entire/cli/cmd/entire/cli/strategy/strategy.go:375`**\\n**`/Users/pfleidi/entire/cli/cmd/entire/cli/strategy/manual_commit.go:100`**\\n**`/Users/pfleidi/entire/cli/cmd/entire/cli/strategy/auto_commit.go:462`**\\n\\n`EnsureSetup() error` is the sole method on the `Strategy` interface that does not accept a `context.Context`. Both implementations use `context.Background()` with `//nolint:contextcheck` annotations. Since this refactoring is specifically about eliminating unnecessary `context.Background()` calls, this is an incomplete migration.\\n\\n```go\\n// strategy.go:375\\nEnsureSetup() error  // No context parameter\\n\\n// manual_commit.go:101\\nfunc (s *ManualCommitStrategy) EnsureSetup() error {\\n    if err := EnsureEntireGitignore(context.Background()); err != nil { //nolint:contextcheck\\n```\\n\\n**Suggested fix:** Update the interface to `EnsureSetup(ctx context.Context) error` and thread the context from callers. If this is intentionally deferred (e.g., too many callers to update in this PR), add a TODO comment at the interface definition explaining the plan.\\n\\n### I2. Dual context parameters in handleAmendCommitMsg\\n\\n**`/Users/pfleidi/entire/cli/cmd/entire/cli/strategy/manual_commit_hooks.go:393`**\\n\\nThis function accepts two `context.Context` parameters:\\n\\n```go\\nfunc (s *ManualCommitStrategy) handleAmendCommitMsg(ctx context.Context, logCtx context.Context, commitMsgFile string) error {\\n```\\n\\nHaving two context parameters is confusing and error-prone. A maintainer must carefully choose between `ctx` and `logCtx` for each call. Compare with `TransitionAndLog` at `/Users/pfleidi/entire/cli/cmd/entire/cli/strategy/session_state.go:162-165` which correctly derives `logCtx` from the main context:\\n\\n```go\\nfunc TransitionAndLog(goCtx context.Context, ...) error {\\n    logCtx := logging.WithComponent(goCtx, \\\"session\\\")  // Derived, not a separate parameter\\n```\\n\\n**Suggested fix:** Accept a single `ctx context.Context` and derive the logging context inside the function:\\n\\n```go\\nfunc (s *ManualCommitStrategy) handleAmendCommitMsg(ctx context.Context, commitMsgFile string) error {\\n    logCtx := logging.WithComponent(ctx, \\\"manual-commit\\\")\\n    // ...\\n}\\n```\\n\\n### I3. postCommitActionHandler stores two context fields\\n\\n**`/Users/pfleidi/entire/cli/cmd/entire/cli/strategy/manual_commit_hooks.go:486-503`**\\n\\nThe `postCommitActionHandler` struct stores both `ctx` and `logCtx` as fields:\\n\\n```go\\ntype postCommitActionHandler struct {\\n    s                      *ManualCommitStrategy\\n    ctx                    context.Context\\n    logCtx                 context.Context\\n    // ...\\n}\\n```\\n\\nStoring contexts in structs is discouraged by Go conventions (see `context` package documentation: \\\"Do not store Contexts inside a struct type\\\"). In this case both fields are used in handler methods, creating ambiguity about which to use for different operations. The `HandleCondense` method (line 505) passes `h.ctx` to `condenseAndUpdateState` but `h.logCtx` to `updateBaseCommitIfChanged`.\\n\\n**Suggested fix:** Store only `ctx` and derive `logCtx` at the point of use in each handler method. This removes the ambiguity and follows Go conventions more closely. Note: I acknowledge the struct-stored-context pattern may be pragmatic here since the handler has a short lifecycle (one PostCommit event), but the dual-context storage adds unnecessary confusion.\\n\\n### I4. Test error messages contain literal \\\"context.Background()\\\" text (cosmetic, find-and-replace artifact)\\n\\n**`/Users/pfleidi/entire/cli/cmd/entire/cli/strategy/clean_test.go:113, 118, 128, 131, 134, 168, 172, 176, 435`**\\n**`/Users/pfleidi/entire/cli/cmd/entire/cli/strategy/session_test.go:202, 206, 223, 231, 235, 263, 272, 276, 298, 353, 367`**\\n(and likely more across 16 test files with 488 total occurrences)\\n\\nError messages in tes